15	//! Dynamic message-derivation check.
16	//!
17	//! Mirrors HS's `Theory.Tools.MessageDerivationChecks.checkVariableDeducability`
18	//! (lib/theory/src/Theory/Tools/MessageDerivationChecks.hs:35-50).  For each
19	//! protocol rule, asks the prover: "given that the intruder has access to all
20	//! of this rule's premise terms, can it derive each of the rule's free
21	//! variables?"  When a variable IS bound by some premise fact but cannot
22	//! actually be derived by the intruder (because the fact's containing rule
23	//! is unreachable / requires private knowledge), HS flags it as an
24	//! "unintended pattern match".
25	//!
26	//! How HS does it (verbatim — see `MessageDerivationChecks.hs:35-50,181-188`):
27	//!
28	//!   For each rule R indexed by idx:
29	//!     1. Drop ALL rules/lemmas/restrictions from the theory, carrying over
30	//!        the signature items (builtins/functions/equations/macros) VERBATIM
31	//!        — privacy flags included.  HS's `makeFunsPublic` and `replacePrivate`
32	//!        both look like they make symbols public but neither changes the
33	//!        verdict: `makeFunsPublic` only sets the OPEN theory's pure signature,
34	//!        which `closeTheoryWithMaude sig` overwrites with the ORIGINAL private-
35	//!        preserving maude signature (so intruder-rule generation stays private);
36	//!        and `replacePrivate` rewrites Out-term heads to a same-name Public
37	//!        variant that gets no construction/destruction rule, leaving the term
38	//!        opaque exactly as the private application would be.  See
39	//!        `synthesise_probe_theory` for the full citation.
40	//!     2. Add a single generated rule:
41	//!          rule Generated_<idx>:
42	//!            [ Fr(~v1), Fr(~v2), ... ]                  // each free var of R
43	//!            --[ Generated_<idx>(v1, v2, ...) ]->        // sole action
44	//!            [ Out(t1), Out(t2), ... ]                   // R's premise terms
45	//!     3. Add one exists-trace lemma per free var v.  HS's `landFormula`
46	//!        gives each conjunct its OWN timepoint via `zip [0..]`, and the
47	//!        intruder-knowledge predicate is `KU` (`lntermToKUFact = kuFact`):
48	//!          lemma deriv_v: exists-trace
49	//!            "Ex v1 v2 ... #t0 #t1. Generated_<idx>(v1, v2, ...) @ #t0 & KU(v) @ #t1"
50	//!     4. Run the prover on each lemma with `--derivcheck-timeout`.
51	//!     5. Lemmas whose proof did NOT find a trace identify non-derivable
52	//!        variables — report them.
53	//!
54	//! Note: `prove_probe` builds the `ProofContext` + runs `ensure_saturated()`
55	//! ONCE per probe and then iterates the per-variable lemmas reusing that
56	//! shared, already-saturated context, so a rule with N free vars incurs N
57	//! proof attempts but only one context build.  Each attempt is bounded by
58	//! the user's timeout (default 5s, mirrored on the HS side).  The check is
59	//! gated by `args.derivcheck_timeout`; passing `0` disables it entirely (HS:
60	//! `Main.TheoryLoader.hs`).
61	
62	use std::time::Duration;
63	use tamarin_parser::ast as p;
64	use tamarin_parser::wf::WfError;
65	use tamarin_term::maude_proc::MaudeHandle;
